data: {"type":"thinking_to_text","data":"The user is asking for a brief explanation of monads. This is a general programming concept question, not specific to their project. I should give a concise, clear explanation without being overly academic.\n\n\n**Monads** are a pattern for chaining operations while handling \"extra stuff\" (like null checks, errors, or async work) cleanly.\n\nThink of it as a **box with rules**:\n\n1. **Wrap** — put a value in the box\n2. **Transform** — run a function that works inside the box\n3. **Unwrap** — get the value back out (or not, depending on the type)\n\n**Why useful:** They let you chain operations without nested if-null checks or try-catch blocks cluttering your code.\n\n**Common examples:**\n\n- **Maybe/Option** — handles null gracefully (skips remaining operations if null)\n- **Result** — captures errors instead of throwing\n- **Promise** — chains async operations\n\n**JavaScript/TypeScript examples you likely use:**\n\n```ts\n// Promise is a monad\nawait fetch('/api')\n  .then(res => res.json())\n  .then(data => process(data))\n  .catch(err => handle(err))\n\n// Optional chaining is like a Maybe monad\nuser?.address?.city?.toUpperCase()\n```\n\nThe key insight: monads abstract away the \"what if something went wrong?\" boilerplate so your business logic stays clean."}

